[size=4][b]🆕 v1.1.161 — Textures Join the Compare[/b][/size]

[list]
[*][b]Every pane can now show a texture[/b], not just a NIF — the same pane, the same thumbnail strip, swapping content as you browse `.dds`/`.png`/`.tga`/`.bmp`[/*]
[*]Smooth pointer zoom, clamped pan, rotation, fit-to-screen, R/G/B/A channel isolation, checkerboard transparency, and mip-level browsing for DDS[/*]
[*][b]Multi-game Game Data[/b] — register Skyrim LE, Skyrim SE and Fallout 4 Data folders all at once; texture lookup is scoped to each NIF's own game so same-named assets can't cross-resolve[/*]
[*]Fixed a regression that could hide the Texture Inspector's preview behind the 3D scene[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]🆕 v1.0.116 — First Release[/b][/size]

Everything below is new. The highlights, if you only read one list:

[list]
[*][b]Up to 8 panes[/b], cameras and lighting synced — built around the Vortex "open every conflicting file" flow[/*]
[*][b]Material diff panel[/b] — a real value-by-value table, not two windows and your memory[/*]
[*][b]Parallax / Complex Material / True PBR[/b] rendering, each toggleable so you can see which path a mesh takes[/*]
[*][b]Animation playback[/b] for animated statics, phase-locked across panes[/*]
[*][b]User-editable shaders[/b] with 1-second hot reload[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]⚡ Why NIFDiff Exists[/b][/size]

NifSkope is the tool everyone uses to inspect a NIF — but when you actually need to answer [i]"what did this mod change?"[/i], you end up:

[list]
[*]Opening two NifSkope windows and eyeballing them back and forth[/*]
[*]Manually matching camera angles that never quite line up[/*]
[*]Digging through block trees to compare two texture slots[/*]
[*]Never quite sure whether a texture came from a loose file or a BSA[/*]
[/list]

[b]NIFDiff is built for the compare itself.[/b] Load both meshes, orbit once — both move together — select a sub-mesh, and a diff table tells you which values actually differ.

[size=4][b]🔍 Side-by-Side Comparison (1–8 Panes)[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]1–8 panes in an equal-width grid (1–4 in a row, 5–8 in two rows), added and removed at runtime[/*]
[*][b]Synced views[/b] — one orbit / pan / zoom moves every model at once[/*]
[*][b]Synced lighting[/b] — one light change hits every pane[/*]
[*][b]Synced files[/b] — stepping to the next mesh in one pane steps every pane to the same file name in its own folder[/*]
[*]Each sync toggles independently, so you can freeze the others for an isolated before/after[/*]
[*][b]SYNCED / UNIQUE badges[/b] flag the odd one out at a glance — a mod that's missing that mesh stands out immediately[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]🧩 Built for Vortex Mod Manager Users[/b][/size]

This is where NIFDiff earns its place in your toolbox.

Vortex's conflict editor lets you open every mod's version of a conflicted file. NIFDiff catches them all through single-instance forwarding and lines them up automatically:

[list]
[*]Open all 8 mods overriding one mesh → [b]one window, 8 panes, all synced[/b][/*]
[*]No manual setup, no dragging files around[/*]
[*]Instantly see which mod's version you're actually getting — and what it costs you[/*]
[/list]

Opening a .nif whose [i]name[/i] matches one already open always lands in a new pane of the same window. Unrelated files start their own window.

[size=4][b]📋 Material Diff Panel — The Actual "Diff"[/b][/size]

Select a sub-mesh and press [b]I[/b]:

[list]
[*]A table of its BSLightingShaderProperty data — shader type and flags, every texture slot, specular / emissive / alpha / UV values, alpha and depth state[/*]
[*]Side by side with the [b]same-named mesh in every other pane[/b], with the differing values highlighted[/*]
[*][b]Loose vs BSA markers[/b] — when two panes resolve the same texture path to different sources, it lights up[/*]
[*]Hover a texture cell for its full path and resolved source; right-click to copy[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]🔬 Texture Inspector[/b][/size]

Press [b]T[/b] to list the selected mesh's bound textures with resolution, pixel format, mip count and resolved source — then preview any slot in 2D with R/G/B/A channel isolation. Read your RMAOS / complex-material channel content without leaving the viewer.

[size=4][b]🖼️ Textures Are First-Class Panes[/b][/size]

Drop a `.dds`/`.png`/`.tga`/`.bmp` onto a pane (or click one in the thumbnail strip) and that pane becomes a full 2D image view — no separate window, no new pane, and the strip keeps browsing right where you left it.

[list]
[*]Smooth pointer zoom, rotation-aware clamped pan, 90°/180° rotation, fit-to-screen and reset[/*]
[*]Switchable smooth/nearest sampling, and a live info bar (dimensions, format, zoom, rotation) — [b]I[/b] opens the full details, including mip level and source compression[/*]
[*]Browse a DDS's mip chain directly ([b]Ctrl+[[/b] / [b]Ctrl+][/b], or the context menu) to see how a texture holds up at a smaller size[/*]
[*]Checkerboard backdrop behind transparency, R/G/B/A channel isolation, and a per-pane Alpha Channel override for the rare texture the automatic transparency-vs-data policy gets wrong[/*]
[*]Compressed DDS (BC1-BC7) uploads straight to the GPU in its native block format — 4K textures open effectively instantly[/*]
[*]With Sync Views on, zoom/pan/channel changes mirror across panes just like the 3D cameras do — line a diffuse up against its normal map, or compare two mods' version of one texture[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]✨ Modern Material Support (Not Just Vanilla)[/b][/size]

[list]
[*][b]Vanilla lit path:[/b] specular, glow/emissive, environment maps with per-material cubemaps, soft/rim/back lighting, model-space normals, multilayer parallax, skin/hair tint, face tint masks, effect shaders, alpha blending/testing, decals, double-sided materials[/*]
[*][b]Parallax[/b] (_p.dds): parallax occlusion mapping with height-field self-shadowing[/*]
[*][b]Complex Material[/b] (ENB / Community Shaders _m.dds): R/G/B/A read as reflection / glossiness / metalness / height, detected by the ecosystem's standard rule — with a CPU-side probe that rejects flat alphas and binary masks so fake "height" fields don't produce garbage POM[/*]
[*][b]True PBR[/b] (Community Shaders / PBRNifPatcher): SLSF2_Unused01 marker, RMAOS slot conventions, GGX/Cook-Torrance shading, displacement POM, and ambient specular from a procedural IBL cubemap so metals get directional, colored reflections[/*]
[*][b]Toggle each path on/off[/b] (Parallax / Complex Mat / True PBR) to see a mesh with vs. without it — the fastest way to find out why one pane looks different[/*]
[/list]

[i]A credible preview, not an ENB/CS-exact reproduction — but close enough to catch what's actually wrong with a mesh.[/i]

[size=4][b]🎬 Animation Playback[/b][/size]

The animated statics of the game world — water wheels, windmills, traps, animated doors — play back right in the viewer:

[list]
[*]Play/Pause, a sequence dropdown ("Idle", "Open", ...), a scrubbable Time slider, Loop, and Speed (0.25–2x)[/*]
[*][b]Sync Anim[/b] keeps every pane on the same clock — two mods' versions of the same animated mesh run side by side [b]in phase[/b][/*]
[*]Idle CPU stays at zero when nothing is playing[/*]
[/list]

[i]Rigid NIF-embedded animations only — actor skeletal animations live in external Havok .hkx files (NifSkope cannot play those either).[/i]

[size=4][b]🧭 Navigation That Doesn't Fight You[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]Left-drag orbit, middle/right-drag pan, wheel zoom toward the cursor — plus the DCC-standard [b]Alt chords[/b] (Alt+Left/Middle/Right) for Maya/Blender muscle memory[/*]
[*][b]On-screen XYZ gizmo[/b] in every pane — click an axis nub to animation-snap to that view[/*]
[*]Blender-style numpad views (1/3/7 = Front/Right/Top, Ctrl for the opposite face, 5 = ortho toggle)[/*]
[*][b]Orthographic mode[/b] — drop perspective so two silhouettes line up 1:1[/*]
[*][b]Orbit around your selection[/b] — the picked sub-mesh stays put while the rest revolves around it[/*]
[*][b]Close-up actually works[/b] — pan and zoom don't freeze as you approach, and zoom can dolly [i]through[/i] the pivot into a model's interior[/*]
[*]Move / Zoom / Rotate sensitivity sliders and an FOV slider, all shared across panes[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]📁 Per-Pane Folder Browser[/b][/size]

Every pane has its own thumbnail strip along its bottom edge, listing the folder of [i]that[/i] pane's open file — so when comparing files from different mod folders, each pane browses its own.

[list]
[*]Sibling .nif files render as real [b]3D thumbnails[/b], framed from a 3/4 angle at each model's own aspect ratio[/*]
[*]Subfolders and a ".." tile for browsing; keyboard navigation with type-to-select[/*]
[*]Generated on a background thread pool — a big folder never blocks or stutters the UI[/*]
[*]Resizable (drag the strip's edge) with Small/Medium/Large presets; toggle all strips off at once[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]🗂️ Correct Bethesda Resource Handling[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]Loads Skyrim LE / Skyrim SE / Fallout 4 NIFs[/*]
[*]Textures resolve in [b]engine order[/b]: override folders → the NIF's own directory → Game Data → BSA/BA2 archives[/*]
[*][b]Multi-game Game Data[/b] — register Skyrim LE, Skyrim SE and Fallout 4 folders at once ([b]Detect[/b] finds every installed game; [b]Set Active[/b] assigns a folder to whichever game the active NIF belongs to). Lookups are scoped per game, so two games' assets sharing a path can't cross-resolve[/*]
[*]An override-folder list for loose texture mods that should win over Game Data[/*]
[*]A named-but-unresolved diffuse renders [b]magenta[/b] instead of quietly blending in as plain white — missing content is unmissable[/*]
[*]Textures are pooled process-wide: each unique resolved source is decoded and uploaded once, shared across every pane[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]🎨 User-Editable Shaders (Advanced)[/b][/size]

The HLSL sources ship next to the exe in a shaders folder. Edit one and save — the app [b]hot-reloads it within a second[/b], no restart. A compile error keeps the previous shaders and shows a toast; a broken edit can never blank the viewer.

You can also [b]route the renderer to your own shaders[/b] per material kind via shaders.ini:

[code]
[Programs]
MyToon=custom\MyToon.hlsl

[Bind.Mesh]
Rule1=pbr -> MyToon
Rule2=* -> Lit
[/code]

Selectors: pbr / complexmat / parallax / envmap / effect / decal / node:<substring> / tex:<substring> / *. The manifest and every shader source hot-reload live, so a single rule can restyle only the True PBR meshes of a compare — thumbnails included — while everything else keeps stock shading. Delete the file for stock behavior (the default — untouched installs pay zero startup cost).

[size=4][b]⌨️ Hotkeys (Everyday Use)[/b][/size]

[list]
[*][b]Left drag / Middle-Right drag / Wheel:[/b] orbit / pan / zoom-to-cursor[/*]
[*][b]Alt + Left/Middle/Right drag:[/b] orbit / pan / dolly (DCC chords)[/*]
[*][b]Numpad 1/3/7:[/b] Front / Right / Top (Ctrl+ for the opposite face) — [b]Numpad 5:[/b] ortho toggle[/*]
[*][b]Numpad . / Numpad 0:[/b] frame selection / whole scene[/*]
[*][b]F / R:[/b] reset all views / active pane's view — [b]C:[/b] focus selected sub-mesh[/*]
[*][b]I / T:[/b] material diff panel / texture inspector[/*]
[*][b]G X W H N Shift+N M:[/b] grid / axes / wireframe / hidden / normals / tangents / MSAA[/*]
[*][b]1–8 / Tab:[/b] select the active pane[/*]
[*][b]Ctrl+O / Ctrl+Shift+O:[/b] open into the active pane / a new pane[/*]
[*][b]Left / Right, Home / End:[/b] step the thumbnail strip — [b]Enter / Backspace:[/b] enter folder / go up[/*]
[*][b]Ctrl+E / F12:[/b] show in Explorer / save a screenshot[/*]
[*][b]Image pane — wheel / drag / F:[/b] zoom / pan / fit to screen — [b][ ] \ Ctrl+[ Ctrl+]:[/b] rotate / mip level[/*]
[/list]

[i]Numpad view keys need NumLock on.[/i]

[size=4][b]🧭 Quick Start[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]Register your [b]Game Data[/b] folders once (RESOURCES group → [b]Detect[/b] finds every installed Skyrim/Fallout install) so BSA/BA2 textures resolve[/*]
[*]Drag & drop .nif files onto a pane — the left ~75% [b]replaces[/b] it, the right ~25% [b]inserts a new pane[/b][/*]
[*]Drop several same-named .nifs at once to line them up in equal panes[/*]
[*]Register the .nif file association to open meshes straight from Explorer or Vortex[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]⚙️ Light and Fast[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]2.3 MB single executable, no installer[/*]
[*]Cold start in about half a second — BSA scanning runs in parallel in the background[/*]
[*]Model loading is async end to end: panes appear immediately, models stream in, textures pop in as they decode[/*]
[*]No Qt, no Electron, no runtime frameworks, no background services[/*]
[*]Full session persistence: open files, pane layout, window position, Game Data path, recent files[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]🎯 Who This Is For[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]Anyone resolving mesh conflicts between mods (especially Vortex users)[/*]
[*]Mesh authors checking their own before/after[/*]
[*]Anyone running Parallax / Complex Material / True PBR setups who needs to know which path a mesh actually takes[/*]
[*]Anyone tired of two NifSkope windows and a lot of squinting[/*]
[/list]

[size=4][b]📋 Requirements[/b][/size]

[list]
[*]Windows 10/11, 64-bit[/*]
[*]A GPU with Direct3D 11 support (anything from the last decade)[/*]
[*]A Skyrim/Fallout Data folder for archive-backed textures (optional — loose files work without it)[/*]
[/list]

[b]The compare tool NifSkope never was: 8 meshes, one camera, and a diff table that tells you what actually changed.[/b]

